I'm gonna pull some numbers out of my ass from a benchmark video I watched a day or two ago
A Ryzen 3900x running on the cheapest, entry level 2133 ram, would achieve 98 fps in a given title

Alright AMD. I see you. First making cores important and now RAM speed.
And when it comes to 1% lows, even comparing 3600 CL16 to 3200 CL14, the difference an be as high as 20 fps
Also, if you like playing large open-world games, you'll want better ram
Fallout 4 is a good example, with your ram quality having a noticeable effect on framerate
However, I wouldn't recommend buying 3600 CL16 unless you REALLY want to squeeze out every last drop of performance and don't care about the cost

I would imagine diminishing returns would exist but thank you for the info. Crazy how computer hardware changes after a few years.

I'm just happy there is competition now with AMD going from the underdog to the king. Shows that Intel really has not been innovating for the past many years.
I looked into that, there are 3 reasons they are struggling atm
1) Their monolith chip design is biting them in the ass.  Turns out that the I/O section of processors really doesn't like die shrinkage
It's why AMD's processors have a 14 nm I/O die, and the actual processors are 7nm
2) In-house fabrication.  They are able to pack more transistors into their processors than any other manufacturer.
That's part of the reason they perform so well in single-thread workloads at 14nm
3) Both of the above.
Specifically, the monolith design reduces yields, because they design the whole processor and produce it all at once
By breaking the chip up into smaller, separate dies, AMD can easily bin multiple parts to create a single processor
And the transistor count is a case of Intel being a victim of their own success
They've refined their 14nm processors so much, that it might take 2 generations of 10nm processors to match the performance
We don't know when they'll finally release their 10nm processors for desktop.  But at this point Intel needs to put out something that's even more powerful than their 14nm++[+] processors
And if [when] Intel is forced to go to a chiplet design, there's no telling how that will affect the performance of their processors.
They could be just as powerful, or they could take serious performance hits.
#EndLesson
Are you saying is that Intel needs a new CPU architecture to compete with AMD?
Yes
They've been working on 10nm for YEARS.  It's why they're still putting out 14nm++++++++++++++++++++++++ processors
If they don't bite the bullet and do something, by the time they finally release 10nm desktop processors, AMD could be on Zen 3 or 4
At which point that "amazing performance" will become moot :|
